\begin{block}{Introduction}
At McMaster Computing and Software outreach, we designed a tool that incorporates educational psychology with our software used for computer science outreach. Kids as young as 10 years old construct images using shapes in the Elm programming language.
Our tool introduces the outputted shapes and the code simultaneously, which creates an instructional design that makes associations between code and output clear, thus reducing load on the working memory. This process allows us to take advantage of cognitive load theory to improve student learning.

\end{block}

\begin{block}{The Original Experiment}
%Written by Paul Chandler and John Sweller, ``Cognitive Load Theory and the Format of Instruction'', includes some of the preliminary experiments on the cognitive load on human brain. In one of the experiments, they created three pictures on wiring of mixed circuits and presented them to three different group of people. A first (diagram-only) group, was shown only the diagram of the circuit, shown in figure. A second (conventional) group was presented the instructions with informational material written in a separate space and so they would have to assimilate the text with the diagram. Finally, a third (modified) group was given the instructions in a modified, integrated version shown in figure shown. As predicted, the first group exhibited the highest performance since they could input all their attention and mental resources into learning diagram in comparison to the second and third group where they had to do mental integrations and process the redundant information.
\begin{itemize}
\item Paul Chandler and John Sweller describe preliminary experiments on cognitive load \cite{cerpa1996some}
\item Created diagrams of wiring of mixed circuits, presented to different groups of people
\item Case A: diagram with information separately (Figure \ref{fig:orig} (a))
\item Case B: modified, integrated version (Figure \ref{fig:orig} (b))
\item Group B$^1$ exhibited highest performance as mental resources were better utilized.
\end{itemize}
